article.description:
Tamika Whitmore scored 14 points -- all in the
first half -- and Anna DeForge had 13 to lead the Indiana Fever to a
77-44 victory over the New York Liberty on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Fever blow out Liberty; move within game of Detroit
article.linkText: Fever blow out Liberty; move within game of Detroit
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The Indiana Fever got off to a fast start and
didn't look back.

Tamika Whitmore scored 14 points -- all in the first half -- and
Anna DeForge had 13 to lead the Fever to a 77-44 victory over the
New York Liberty on Tuesday night.

Whitmore had seven points as Indiana jumped out to an 11-0 lead,
before Loree Moore hit a 3-pointer 5½ minutes into the game to
get New York on the board.

"We just focused on what we had to do as a team," Whitmore
said. "It wasn't like we came in with the intention to ram it down
their throat or get a big gap like we did. We just played
basketball."

Tamika Catchings added 12 points for the Fever (20-11), who won
their third straight and fourth in five games. Indiana moved one
game behind second-place Detroit with three games to play. The
Fever and Shock will meet in the best-of-three first round of the
playoffs, beginning Aug. 17, though home-court for the series is
still undecided.

"We're just now starting to jell together," Whitmore said.
"Everything's coming together at the right time, especially going
into the playoffs."

Indiana won all three meetings this season, winning the series
for the fourth straight year. The Fever also beat the Liberty for
the sixth straight time, including a sweep in the playoffs last
year.

"We came into this arena wanting to get another win," Indiana
coach Brian Winters said. "We are in a race with Detroit for
home-court. We had a really good defensive effort. After we saw New
York beat Detroit (last Thursday), we weren't going to allow that
to happen to us tonight."

Cathrine Kraayeveld scored 13 points and Ashley Battle had 10
for New York (9-23), which has lost two straight after winning five
of six. The Liberty finished with a season-low scoring total, and
had a franchise-low five points in the third quarter.

"We took a step back tonight, and I'm not sure why," Liberty
coach Pat Coyle said. "We couldn't catch, shoot or pass the ball.
They are a good team. They're in the playoffs for a reason."

Indiana, which led 38-22 at halftime, put the game out of reach
in the third. Kraayeveld had a layup with 4:48 left to pull New
York to 47-24, then made two free throws 1:15 later, and Barbara
Farris hit a free throw with 1:08 left to make it 56-27.

Olympia Scott twice gave Indiana a 37-point lead, the last on a
jumper with 4:41 left to stretch the advantage to 68-31.

The Fever handed the Liberty their fourth-largest loss of the
season. New York had a franchise-record 37-point loss against
Seattle on July 22, and two 35-point defeats earlier.

Whitmore, who spent five seasons in New York after being drafted
by the Liberty in 1999, said it is tough watching her former team
struggle through its worst season.

"I look at them and watch them play, it's hard to watch them go
through it," she said. "I say a prayer for them and wish them the
best. Hopefully they can turn it around, turn it around soon. It's
almost like watching them in slow motion."

Indiana fell one point shy of matching the largest margin of
victory in franchise history, set in an 81-47 win against San Antonio
on July 23, 2003.

Becky Hammon, playing for just the second time in 13 games due
to a sprained left ankle, scored seven points in 18 minutes for the
Liberty.

"She looked better than she did against Connecticut (on Aug.
1)," Coyle said. "She moved better. Her explosiveness isn't back
but it's better than it was the other night."

Battle hit a 3 less than a minute after Moore, but the Fever
scored the next 10 points to take a 21-6 lead with 9 minutes left
in the second quarter.

"We played like garbage on the offensive end," Hammon said.
"They had us well-scouted and we got rattled from the start. We
never calmed down."

Tully Bevilaqua made two free throws to push Indiana's lead to
37-15 with 2:09 left before halftime.
